 					<h2> Part 4: Git started</h2>

 					<p> Now we have a program lets use some version control. Type in the following 4 commands in sequence</p>
 					<pre class="raw_code">
git init
git add -A
git status
git commit -m "initialize"
 					</pre>
 					<p>
 						Does yours look like mine??
 					</p>
 					<img class="img-responsive img-rounded" src="/img/tut0_4.png"/>
 					<p>
 						Lets break it down line by line 
 					</p>
 					<p> <b> git init</b>
 						This is initializing an empty git repo at the current location
 					</p>
 					<p> <b> git add -A</b>
 						<em> git add</em> adds files to the git repo. For example, <b>$ git add helloworld.rb</b> would also have added our file. However, we used the suffix -A instead because it searches and finds all valid options and adds them.
 					</p>
 					<p> <b> git status</b>
 						Status states whats current on the stage. This step isn't necessary but I want to exspose some of the internal working of git. You can think of it like this: In a git repo, a file has 3 states [ indepenent, on stage , committed]. A commited file is a file with a history in the repo, an independent file is not a part of the repo. Either it hasn't been added to or it demeed unneceasry anymore and was removed from the repo. The final one is the stage. This is what status tells us, the stage is important because these are the files of interest for this commit. Its how git determines what files are going to cause merge conflicts. It'll be come clearer the more we play with git.  
 					</p>
 					<p> <b> git commit -m "initialize"</b>
 						Commits are the cornerstone of git. Commits are the nodes in the branching graphs in Git. For those unfamiliar with graph thoery, commits are the different version builds they are solid merged states. Git can revert back to any git commit. Each on of those dots are a different commit. The current build is at dev but you could move the program back to a previous node like feature_x and change all of ur current files back to that old state.
 					</p>
 					<img class="img-rounded img-responsive" src="http://gitguru.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/02/sd_merge.png"></img>

