 					<p> Now lets save your progress with</p>
 					<pre class="raw_code">
git add -A
git commit -m "added one more line"
 					</pre>
 					<p> Now your git is up to date. However...what if we wanted to undo this change? well one way is to move back a commit</p>
 					<p> We accomplish this by typing in the following</p>
 					<pre class="raw_code">
git reset --hard HEAD~1
 					</pre>
 					<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert"><b>Note:</b> That is HEAD~1 with a tilde not a minus sign</div>
 					<p> Now that should have removed our changes and reverted us back to the old version. You can check this out by typing in <b> $ ruby helloworld.rb</b>. While this solution works its like killing a fly with a bazooka</p>
 					<p> Now we can always just edit what we want to undo and just make a new commit. However when handling thousands of files...that option isn't a small task. So why don't we employ a more sophisticated solution to a making a minor change. </p>
 					<p> open Hello world up again using nano <b> $ nano helloworld.rb</b> and copy the following: </p>
 					<pre> 
