 						</code>
 					</pre>
 					<p> Now add and commit. Ex: <b>$ git add -A && git commit -m "Base Commit"</b></p>
 					<p> If you want to see what just happened to your git repo use the command <b>$git show</b>. This shows you the commit message as well as showing you the different changes made at this level. You can go and manual undo those changes</p>
 					<p> Next lets do some branching. Branches are useful for when you want to develop a particular feature or make a major change but don't know how it will affect the rest of the system. So you create a seperate version just for yourself to experiement. Then when you have solved all the issues you can merge it with the master</p>

 					<pre class="raw_code">
 						git branch branching_method
 						git checkout branching_method
 					</pre>
 					<p><b>$ git branch BRANCH_NAME</b> makes a new git branch</p>
 					<p><b>$ git checkout BRANCH_NAME</b> moves the HEAD pointer to this named branch</p>
 					<p> You can actually combine the two commands into <b>$ git checkout -b BRANCH_NAME </b></p>
 					<p> Now remove everything in helloworld.rb and copy this:</p>
 					<pre>
