 					<p> However, if you type in <b>$git checkout master</b> and run <b> $ruby helloworld.rb</b> it should print out <b>Base Branch \n FuzzBuzz</b></p>

 					<h2> Part 6: Merging </h2>

 					<p> The next major topic is merging. Merging allows you to combine different branches together. I will demonstrate how to use git's tools to handle merge conflictions.</p><p> Now lets make sure our head is at master <b> $git checkout master</b> now lets change the code to helloworld.rb</p>

 					<pre>
 						<code class="ruby">
puts "Local Branch"

class Foo
attr_accessor :bar
def initialize(b)
@bar = b
end

def local_branch
"Local branch method"
end 
end

f = Foo.new("FuzzBuzz")
puts f.bar

 						</code>
 					</pre>
 					<p> now add and commit <b> $git commit -a -m "Local Branch"</b></p>

 					<p> run <b> $ ruby helloworld.rb</b></p>
 					<p> Should return <b> Local Branch FuzzBuzz </b></p>
 					<p> okay now run <b>$ git merge branching_branch </b></p>
 					<p> You should get this message</p>
 					<pre class="raw_code">
$ git merge branching_branch
Auto-merging helloworld.rb
CONFLICT (content): Merge conflict in helloworld.rb
Automatic merge failed; fix conflicts and then commit the result.
 					</pre>
 					<p> So we now need to clean up and resolve the merge issues before we can proceed. Type in <b> $git status </b> </p>

 					<img src="/img/tut0_git_status.png" class="img-responsive img-rounded">

 					<p> It will state we have merge issues. So we need to resolve this. We can manually go through our files and find the instances where there are <===HEAD== like comments. Unforunately we could easily miss one going that route. Instead we will use git's mergetools</p>

 					<p> For this tutorial, we will be using kdiff3 since it is a cross platform program. 
 					<% if os == "mac" %>
 						To install kdiff3 for mac, type in this code into the terminal<b> $ brew install kdiff3</b></p>
 					<% elsif os == "linux" %>
 						To install kdiff3 for ubuntu, type in this code into the terminal<b> $ sudo apt-get install kdiff3</b></p>
 					<% else %>
 						To install kdiff3 for windows, download and install this program and then edit the file at "C:/Users/YOUR_USER/.gitconfig" with your text editor. Add these lines to the bottom of it
 						<pre class="raw_code">
[merge]
	tool = kdiff3
[mergetool "kdiff3"]
	path = C:/Program Files/KDiff3/kdiff3.exe
	keepBackup = false
	trustExitCode = true
 						</pre> 
 					<% end %>
 					

 					<p> After a successful installation now run this command to configure git to use it. <b>$ git config --global merge.tool kdiff3</b></p>

 					<p>Now type in <b>$git mergetool </b> and then enter</p>
 					<img src="/img/tut0_7.png" class="img-responsive img-rounded">
 					<img src="/img/tut0_8.png" class="img-responsive img-rounded">

 					<p> This will bring up the kdiff3 tool. It allows use to handle 3 way merging of our files as well as navigate us between conflicts.</p>

 					<p> The structure of these 4 windows is as such:</p>
 					<pre class="raw_code">
| Base | Local | Remote |
|        Merge          |
 					</pre>

 					<p>so Local is the current branch we are at the end of master </p>
 					<p>Remote is the branch we are merging with so Branching_branch</p>
 					<p>Base is the last commit these two branches have in common and Merge is the result we want. Just edit Merge how you want.  </p>

 					<p> A few buttons to keep in mind are the A,B,C buttons. They import the differences of A:Base, B:Local and C:Remote directly into Merge. Once Merge is how you want it to be, hit the save icon in the left corner.</p>
 					<p> The first conflict we don't want any of the three choices. So we will skip it. Use the 3 Downarrow button. Now select B & C. Based upon how these methods were spaced out. They may take up the same line so manual editing may be required. Hit the 3 Uparrow button to return to the first conflict. Now just pick one from A,B,C and just type in the following: <b> puts "Merged Commit"</b></p>
 					<p> The merged result should look like this:</p>
 					<pre>
 						<code class="ruby">
puts "Merged Commit"

class Foo
attr_accessor :bar
def initialize(b)
@bar = b
end

def local_method
return true
end

def branching_method
return true
end
end

f = Foo.new("FuzzBuzz")
puts f.bar

 						</code>
 					</pre>

 					<p> Now save and quit this program</p>
